postcontent: This is an absolutely beautiful CMP 1955 Springfield (SA) Armory M1 Garand; the rifle that General George S. Patton referred to as: " the greatest battlefield implement ever devised." She was originally purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program.The rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 cartridge. The SA barrel dates to 4-55. The SA rifle serial number dates to 1955 as well. That, along with like condition and Patina, suggests the barrel is original to the gun. The serial number will be given upon phone conversation only. There are no visible import marks. The stainless gas seal is the only area exhibiting any significant wear. Rust is non-existent, nor are there any signs of major battle scars. Normal wear is minimal for the time frame. The stock is a post WWII Overton Stock with evidence of a faint DOD cartouche stamp. The barrel is shiny and remains accurate. The rifle functions wonderfully and is accompanied by 5 en bloc clips. The rifle wears an OD nylon sling, befitting of the time period in both use and appearance. The weapon has the normal matching of the major US manufacturers parts of that time:Receiver- SABarrel- 4-1955Trigger Group- International Harvester Op Rod- SA Bolt- Harrington and RichardsonSights (SA). The sights are in excellent mechanical condition and show minimal wear. They remain audible, tactile and precise on the firing line.Stock- OvertonME- 2Do not have a chamber guage, but throat wear is minimal. Casing test shows a solid 1/8" of the top of the casing, so it's definitely not "swallowing" it. title: For Sale:  Winchester 1890 .22 WRF XCond 1905 C&R
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: This Winchester 1890 2nd Model take-down slide action rifle, chambered in .22 WRF in highly collectible condition. Make room in the gun safe you are going to want this one; it is all original & the condition is exceptional, especially considering it is 112 years old. This round (also known as .22 Remington Special) was the “Magnum” of its day. The 1890 was designed by John Browning & was the first pump rifle sold by Winchester. These were manufactured from 1890 to 1932, according to the Cody Polishing Room Records this rifle was produced in 1905. Mechanically sound; functions correctly & safely with no issues. The action is crisp & smooth & the rifle is still very accurate. The bore is in excellent condition: bright & shiny with no frosting. It has a clean bolt face, the inside of the receiver still has most of its bluing, shows little signs of use. It has a 24” octagon barrel with the original sights; the front sight has a patent date of Nov 4, 1902 & the rear sight patent date is Jan. 29, 1901. The bluing is bright & shiny, deep & rich, incredible for the age. The barrel corners are still sharp, all stampings are clear & legible, there is very little bluing loss, mostly limited to some of the high spots. Minor handling marks & a few pin-head pits are found upon up-close inspection. The stocks are walnut with nice grain & finish & are solid with no cracks or repairs, just minor handling marks. The pump handle has 12 grooves, it has a Crescent butt stock with a case colored steel butt plate. The wood fits proud to the metal & the finish is original.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1890 .22 WRF XCond 1905 C&R
location: North Carolina, North Carolina, United States
postcontent: This Winchester 1890 2nd Model take-down slide action rifle, chambered in .22 WRF in highly collectible condition. Make room in the gun safe you are going to want this one; it is all original & the condition is exceptional, especially considering it is 112 years old. This round (also known as .22 Remington Special) was the “Magnum” of its day. The 1890 was designed by John Browning & was the first pump rifle sold by Winchester. These were manufactured from 1890 to 1932, according to the Cody Polishing Room Records this rifle was produced in 1905. Mechanically sound; functions correctly & safely with no issues. The action is crisp & smooth & the rifle is still very accurate. The bore is in excellent condition: bright & shiny with no frosting. It has a clean bolt face, the inside of the receiver still has most of its bluing, shows little signs of use. It has a 24” octagon barrel with the original sights; the front sight has a patent date of Nov 4, 1902 & the rear sight patent date is Jan. 29, 1901. The bluing is bright & shiny, deep & rich, incredible for the age. The barrel corners are still sharp, all stampings are clear & legible, there is very little bluing loss, mostly limited to some of the high spots. Minor handling marks & a few pin-head pits are found upon up-close inspection. The stocks are walnut with nice grain & finish & are solid with no cracks or repairs, just minor handling marks. The pump handle has 12 grooves, it has a Crescent butt stock with a case colored steel butt plate. The wood fits proud to the metal & the finish is original.
